Here is a simple function that converts some basic Markdown formatting to HTML. This implementation only supports a subset of Markdown syntax, such as headers, emphasis, links, and lists. You can extend it to support more Markdown elements as needed.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown)
{
    std::string html;

    // Header
    std::regex header_regex("# (.*)");
    std::string replacement("<h1>$1</h1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, header_regex, replacement);

    // Emphasis
    std::regex emphasis_regex("(_(.*)_)|(\*(.*)*)" );
    std::string emphasis_replacement("<em>$2</em>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, emphasis_regex, emphasis_replacement);

    // Links
    std::regex link_regex("\\[(.*)\\]\\((.*)\\)");
    std::string link_replacement("<a href='$2'>$1</a>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, link_regex, link_replacement);

    // Lists
    std::regex list_regex("^([*]+)(.*)$");
    std::string list_replacement("<ul><li>$3</li></ul>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, list_regex, list_replacement);

    return html;
}
```

To use this function, simply call it with a markdown formatted string:

```cpp
std::string markdownText = "# My Header\n\n* List item 1\n* List item 2\n\n[Link Text](https://example.com)";
std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
```

This implementation is not perfect and may not handle all Markdown cases correctly. For a more comprehensive solution, consider using an existing Markdown parsing library or writing a more sophisticated parser.


